{"term":"1976","caseName":"Ingraham v. Wright","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1976/75-6527","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 02, 1976","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger6/oral_argument_audio/16108","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear arguments next in 6527 Ingraham against Wright.","start":0,"stop":46.869,"duration":46.87},{"text":"Mr. Rogow you may proceed whenever you are ready.","start":46.869,"stop":50.262,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief justice and may it please the court.","start":50.262,"stop":53.006,"duration":2.74},{"text":"There are three issues in this case; the first issue is whether or not the Eighth Amendment is cruel on unusual punishment clause, has any application to public school students who are beaten by their teachers or principals.","start":53.006,"stop":67.251,"duration":14.25},{"text":"The United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit held an affect that no matter how brutal how severe, how excessive the beating is inflicted upon public schools students, they may seek no relief under the Eighth Amendment that is the first issue.","start":67.251,"stop":80.63,"duration":13.38},{"text":"The second issue is if the Eighth Amendment does apply as we submit it does.","start":80.63,"stop":85.674,"duration":5.04},{"text":"Whether or not the facts of this case show that these student’s Eighth Amendment’s right have been violated, The third issue which is separate and distinct, is whether or not any corporal punishment inflicted by an instrument designed to cause bodily injury, whether or not that punishment must be proceeded by some opportunity to be heard under the 14th Amendment’s Due Process Clause.","start":85.674,"stop":111.16,"duration":25.49},{"text":"The Court of Appeal’s decision was that there was no need for such a hearing.","start":111.16,"stop":116.159,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rogow you are going to discuss those point by point.","start":116.159,"stop":119.128,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, I will Mr. Justice Rehnquist.","start":119.128,"stop":120.508,"duration":1.38},{"text":"In fact I turned out to the Eighth Amendment argument.","start":120.508,"stop":125.437,"duration":4.93},{"text":"The effect of the Court of Appeals decision as I mentioned is to give carte blanche to teachers and principals to punish corporally as severely as excessively as they may do and there will be no recourse under the Eighth Amendment.","start":125.437,"stop":140.16,"duration":14.72},{"text":"The decision seems to focus on the issue of whether or not the punishment is imposed in a criminal setting or a civil setting and the Court of Appeals held that the Eighth Amendment only applies in the criminal context.","start":140.16,"stop":152.691,"duration":12.53},{"text":"We believe that decision misses the point of the Eighth Amendment.","start":152.691,"stop":156.507,"duration":3.82},{"text":"The focus of the Eighth Amendment is upon punishment, it is not upon who delivers the punishment.","start":156.507,"stop":164.427,"duration":7.92},{"text":"The original purpose of…","start":164.427,"stop":166.877,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"You said has no focus on who delivers it.","start":166.877,"stop":169.47,"duration":2.59},{"text":"If a stranger walks up to you on the streets and hits you over the head with the club that’s probably is some punishment, now does the Eighth Amendment apply there?","start":169.47,"stop":178.196,"duration":8.73}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No it does not Mr. Chief Justice because…","start":178.196,"stop":179.731,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We are talking about the authority of government in somewhere.","start":179.731,"stop":183.527,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly punishment imposed under color of State Law which are the facts of this case and which is the kind of punishment we are talking about here.","start":183.527,"stop":191.738,"duration":8.21},{"text":"The original purpose of the Eighth Amendment was to preclude the barbaric kinds of punishments which were known in the 15th, 16th, 17th, 18th centuries in England and on the continent.","start":191.738,"stop":202.638,"duration":10.9},{"text":"To be sure the drafters look back, looked at history and saw terrible punishments imposed in a criminal context generally and that is what they sought to ban in the Eighth Amendment because that is what they saw in the past, but that does not mean that there was to be no ban on punishments imposed by other people acting under color of State Law if those punishments were excessive and severe.","start":202.638,"stop":228.468,"duration":25.83}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rogow you were here this morning, weren't you doing the argument of the fight in the Columbus bar case.","start":228.468,"stop":233.594,"duration":5.13}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes I was Mr. Justice.","start":233.594,"stop":234.744,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You have heard some of the questioning there supposing the policemen in that case had simply pistol-whipped with one of the plaintiffs there, would you say that could be a cruel and unusual punishment.","start":234.744,"stop":248.372,"duration":13.63}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"If he had done it as a summary punishment in arresting the person, take him into custody and then similarly punishing him depriving him of the right to be trailed then I could say that would be a violation of due process right but not cruel and unusual punishment.","start":248.372,"stop":264.805,"duration":16.43}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Why would you say, it wasn’t a cruel and unusual punishment?","start":264.805,"stop":268.487,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say it wasn’t the cruel unusual punishment because, it’s a difficult question Mr. Justice Rehnquist probably because if he is not been addressed in that context, generally there was another clear constitutional right that has been violated but as I reflect on it, I think that could begin to give rise to a cruel unusual punishment, the only withdrawing I might do from that position might be that, that kind of punishment is not authorized at all by law, with the kind of punishment we are talking about here is at the outset authorized by law and then it’s exceeded.","start":268.487,"stop":304.01,"duration":35.52}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rogow you admit that during the time of adoption of Eighth Amendment corporal punishment was the order of the day.","start":304.01,"stop":311.729,"duration":7.72}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes it was in a limited context reasonable corporal punishment.","start":311.729,"stop":316.261,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"He made it a criminal by whipping with the stick.","start":316.261,"stop":319.45,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"They did and this court has recognized all that the Eighth Amendment is a dynamic evolving concept and what may have been tolerated at the time of the adoption of the Eighth Amendment hasn’t been tolerated as we progressed in our society standards of decency and civilized notions.","start":319.45,"stop":335.246,"duration":15.8}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"You take position that all corporal punishments and violations?","start":335.246,"stop":338.734,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No we do not Mr. Justice Marshall.","start":338.734,"stop":341.148,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Then why are you arguing in this case?","start":341.148,"stop":342.959,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"We are only arguing this case and we are saying that reasonable corporal punishment will not be a violation of the Eighth Amendment.","start":342.959,"stop":349.407,"duration":6.45},{"text":"We are saying that physical corporal punishment imposed by an instrument will have to be proceeded by an opportunity for hearing that is our Fourteenth Amendment argument which is separate and distinct from this, but we are not seeking to outlaw all corporal punishment in a public school context Mr. Justice Marshall.","start":349.407,"stop":366.32,"duration":16.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What would be the issue of the hearing?","start":366.32,"stop":368.668,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"The issue would be at that hearing whether or not the student did in fact commit the offence for which she has been punished.","start":368.668,"stop":374.671,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And also even if he did, whether or not corporal punishment…","start":374.671,"stop":378.686,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly the kind of punishment that ought to be inflicted.","start":378.686,"stop":381.775,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"What constitutional interest under your Fourteenth Amendment argument is the student deprived without due process of law if such a hearing is not held?","start":381.775,"stop":389.697,"duration":7.92}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"He is deprived of the liberty interest Mr. Justice Rehnquist.","start":389.697,"stop":393.583,"duration":3.89},{"text":"A liberty interest that is drawn really from nearly all the Amendments of the constitution.","start":393.583,"stop":399.933,"duration":6.35}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"All 26?","start":399.933,"stop":400.988,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No I’m sorry at least the first ten, Mr. Justice Rehnquist.","start":400.988,"stop":404.819,"duration":3.83},{"text":"The liberty interest, the right to be treated with human dignity is at least in interest and liberty.","start":404.819,"stop":409.985,"duration":5.17}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is the right to be treated with human dignity where is that stated in the constitution?","start":409.985,"stop":413.713,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not specifically stated –","start":413.713,"stop":414.892,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It's among the per-numbers.","start":414.892,"stop":416.712,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Among the per-numbers and included among the per-numbers are -- and let me list those rights that have been violated, that we think make up the constellation of factors involving liberty.","start":416.712,"stop":426.553,"duration":9.84},{"text":"The right to be free from bodily restraint and a student is restraint, the right to be free from…","start":426.553,"stop":431.153,"duration":4.6}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"What source is, rename the Amendment which is the source.","start":431.153,"stop":436.286,"duration":5.13}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"I can't name specific Amendments I can come to the Fourth Amendment perhaps with the physical kind of intrusion that’s involved but this court is never required a specific Amendment to be named when one is talking about liberty because the concept of liberty is broad and it includes an awful lot of privileges that are essential to the practice of the liberty by free people and free children.","start":436.286,"stop":459.924,"duration":23.64}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Would any one person thinks of it?","start":459.924,"stop":461.867,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No it is not Mr. Justice Marshall.","start":461.867,"stop":463.597,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Would any five think of it?","start":463.597,"stop":466.465,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"It maybe…","start":466.465,"stop":467.204,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that what you think liberty is?","start":467.204,"stop":468.545,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No I think liberty is something that…","start":468.545,"stop":469.518,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"You don’t have to pinpoint?","start":469.518,"stop":470.902,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"I think we do have to pinpoint it, and I’m attempting to pinpoint it by looking at a host of factors which this court has looked at many times in deciding whether or not there is or is not a liberty interest, the freedom from bodily restraint, from bodily intrusion, by officers acting under color of State Law beatings in affect, the freedom from being stigmatized ridiculed, psychologically harmed, having one’s privacy invaded, having one’s reputation, honor and integrity invaded.","start":470.902,"stop":497.141,"duration":26.24},{"text":"When the government does that acting under the color of state law we submit that those things constitute of deprivation of liberty, but that Mr. Justice Marshall is my due process argument and I would like to give back to my Eighth Amendment argument and then address these due process issues once again.","start":497.141,"stop":514.756,"duration":17.61},{"text":"The court is recognized in the Eighth Amendment concept because we think this is important that a principle to be vital must be capable of wider application and the mischief which gave it birth.","start":514.756,"stop":524.178,"duration":9.42},{"text":"The court said that in Weems versus United States where it held unconstitutional as an Eighth Amendment violation.","start":524.178,"stop":530.237,"duration":6.06},{"text":"12 years of hard labor for fraudulently signing a public document and in Robinson versus California the court held that imprisonment for drug addiction could amount to cruel and unusual punishment.","start":530.237,"stop":541.411,"duration":11.17},{"text":"So the court has recognized that the Eighth Amendment is a dynamic evolving concept and that it focuses upon punishment and that’s what we have in this case, we have excessive punishment that the Fifth Circuit would tolerate and say the Eighth Amendment offers no relief from it.","start":541.411,"stop":557.356,"duration":15.95}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Can the Eighth Amendment go backwards as well as forwards, if something is a cruel unusual punishment ten years ago, if evidence shows that there is a great deal of need for it and the need cannot be met in another ways could have done something become not cruel and unusual?","start":557.356,"stop":573.898,"duration":16.54}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"There certainly could be changing and evolving standards of what would be tolerated by society.","start":573.898,"stop":578.991,"duration":5.09},{"text":"So, there could be some change because as I said the Fifth Circuit is flexible and dynamic -- I’m sorry the Eighth Amendment is flexible and dynamic.","start":578.991,"stop":587.78,"duration":8.79},{"text":"The Fifth Circuit was not so flexible in this court, this case.","start":587.78,"stop":594.948,"duration":7.17},{"text":"Because we think the Eighth Amendment applies, we turn to the facts of this case, which we think shows a violation of the Eighth Amendment and these are the facts.","start":594.948,"stop":605.284,"duration":10.34},{"text":"At least four of the people who testified, four of the children these are 13, 14, 15 year old children had to receive medical treatment.","start":605.284,"stop":613.074,"duration":7.79},{"text":"One of them James Ingraham suffered a severe hematoma he was unable to sit down for three weeks, another Roosevelt Andrews loss the use of his hand and had to seek medical attention, another one had a lump on his forehead from the paddle which had to be lanced surgically treated and left a scar, another Daniel Lee.","start":613.074,"stop":631.109,"duration":18.04}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understand the testimony of these boys are all un-contradicted.","start":631.109,"stop":634.665,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes it was.","start":634.665,"stop":635.02,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"There is a record to explain why did the people who administered the discipline did not testify.","start":635.02,"stop":640.107,"duration":5.09}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Because there was a 41-B dismal under the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure in effect of motion for directed verdict at the end of the plaintiff’s case was granted.","start":640.107,"stop":648.914,"duration":8.81}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":648.914,"stop":649.534,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"So the case is resolved with that point in the district court.","start":649.534,"stop":652.933,"duration":3.4},{"text":"Daniel Lee fractured his hand and had a dislocated knuckle, which the district court looked at in the record saw that there was scar even still left from that.","start":652.933,"stop":662.389,"duration":9.46},{"text":"People missed school, some of the descriptions that are involved in this record are unique we think in the annals of punishment in the educational setting.","start":662.389,"stop":670.896,"duration":8.51},{"text":"Children hollering, crying, praying, screaming and yet still being punished and one Rodney William said that he was begging for mercy as he was hit with the paddle and then he was hit with the belt and then his words and tears was coming out of me.","start":670.896,"stop":684.773,"duration":13.88},{"text":"They were repeated blows 50 blows to one student for allegedly making a obscene telephone call.","start":684.773,"stop":691.71,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Granted all this professor, does the Eighth Amendment still apply?","start":691.71,"stop":697.928,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"It applies.","start":697.928,"stop":699.525,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Another three parts of the Eighth Amendment are there, accessing bail and fines both of which are in the criminal context.","start":699.525,"stop":708.695,"duration":9.17}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes they are.","start":708.695,"stop":709.628,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"You are stating in that cruel and unusual punishment necessarily goes beyond the criminal context.","start":709.628,"stop":715.587,"duration":5.96}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the focus is upon punishment and merely as I said before Mr. Justice.","start":715.587,"stop":719.779,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think the founders felt that when they formulated the Eighth Amendment?","start":719.779,"stop":725.18,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s hard for me to state what exactly the founders felt but I believe that they must have thought that punishment imposed by the government cannot be so severe and so excessive that it would amount to the kind of violations of human dignity which they saw occurring in the near past, in England and along the continent.","start":725.18,"stop":744.505,"duration":19.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there a concept of custody that offends your definition of punishment under the Eighth Amendment as must the person inflicting the punishment presumably on behalf of the government have the person is some sort of custody where in affect he can't get away.","start":744.505,"stop":762.367,"duration":17.86}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Not, it is not necessary to my analysis of the Eighth Amendment but there is in some limited way that custody concept even here in a public school setting.","start":762.367,"stop":772.199,"duration":9.83}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But surely it is not necessary to your analysis.","start":772.199,"stop":774.829,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don’t tie it to custody.","start":774.829,"stop":776.587,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What if one superior in the local government office simply pistol-whipped so they would be cruel and unusual if performed by a jailor on an inmate, would that be a cruel unusual punishment?","start":776.587,"stop":790.443,"duration":13.86}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"If it were done for the purpose of punishment, perhaps it could reach to the level of Eighth Amendment violation.","start":790.443,"stop":797.098,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In one of our conferences, one of those hit the other in the nose.","start":797.098,"stop":807.653,"duration":10.56}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t think that kind of force does not rise to the excessive punishment that we are talking about.","start":807.653,"stop":814.13,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Agents of the federal government run federal business.","start":814.13,"stop":818.245,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"But you were not punishing someone, under authority given to you by Federal Law or by State Law in this case.","start":818.245,"stop":826.198,"duration":7.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The authority is to conform sometimes the conference is going to get quite heated.","start":826.198,"stop":830.566,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And it is also to try to get this decree.","start":830.566,"stop":834.094,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"The authority maybe to be conform Mr. Justice Stuart but the authority is not to punish and in the case that we are talking about the authority to the school master heads is to punish, when he exceeds that authority, then in such a severe and excessive way than one gets over in to an Eighth Amendment violation.","start":834.094,"stop":854.627,"duration":20.53}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Professor what did you do about the local (Inaudible), is it gone?","start":854.627,"stop":857.836,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No it is not gone.","start":857.836,"stop":860.168,"duration":2.33},{"text":"There are several things that I do with that Mr. Justice Marshall.","start":860.168,"stop":863.613,"duration":3.45},{"text":"The first is to explain it in its historical concept.","start":863.613,"stop":866.396,"duration":2.78},{"text":"First of all it was the product of a voluntary school or educational system, were parents could choose to send their children, or not send their children to school.","start":866.396,"stop":874.526,"duration":8.13},{"text":"That is not the situation today, children must be sent to school and to some extent that ties in with the custody notion that is involved here.","start":874.526,"stop":884.215,"duration":9.69},{"text":"Secondly, if parents have some way at least to say I withdraw my this assumed delegation to a teacher then perhaps one could say well there may not need to be a hearing before the punishment is imposed because the parent has already given their authority to do it, but there cannot be that withdrawal the way the law stands today.","start":884.215,"stop":907.669,"duration":23.45},{"text":"So, a parent is committed to sending his children to school, he has no say or she has no say, about what kind of punishment is inflicted in that school and we submit at the local parent’s argument does not permit because there has been assumed delegation excessive beatings and it doesn’t permit of beating without an opportunity for a hearing.","start":907.669,"stop":927.705,"duration":20.04}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you analogizing this to a military service under the draft for example and would you say there that a person in a military service who was required for some disciplinary reason to stand up for 48 hours or some such thing would be within the reach of Eighth Amendment.","start":927.705,"stop":951.327,"duration":23.62}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"That person could be, if the punishment was excessive.","start":951.327,"stop":955.913,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Make it to 96 hours and certainly that could be excessive would it not?","start":955.913,"stop":962.789,"duration":6.88}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"As I say it depends upon the facts of the case, it would seem to me that the 96 hours of standing would be excessive punishment and it is punishment.","start":962.789,"stop":971.175,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"And if that were ordered by a superior officer in the circumstances where you have to comply then you say that the Eighth Amendment would be invoked.","start":971.175,"stop":978.655,"duration":7.48}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"It could be invoked, yes Mr. Chief Justice.","start":978.655,"stop":982.971,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rogow you ask for damages and your complaint, this is the forwarded case isn’t it?","start":982.971,"stop":989.88,"duration":6.91}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes it is.","start":989.88,"stop":990.66,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any possibility; are there other Tort remedies under Florida Law for this kind of thing?","start":990.66,"stop":995.866,"duration":5.21}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes there are.","start":995.866,"stop":1000.136,"duration":4.27},{"text":"The due process right to be heard, which we argue is not titled at all to the Eighth Amendment argument.","start":1000.136,"stop":1008.071,"duration":7.94},{"text":"We are not saying one can justify severe and excessive beatings by giving a hearing before one administers those kinds of beatings.","start":1008.071,"stop":1015.253,"duration":7.18},{"text":"What we are saying is when one is beaten with an instrument designed to cause bodily injury, that beating infringes upon the liberty rights.So liberty rights…","start":1015.253,"stop":1023.32,"duration":8.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean to slap?","start":1023.32,"stop":1024.563,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No I do not mean to slap Mr. Justice.","start":1024.563,"stop":1026.88,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I guess a slap will not be an instrument, which will invoke the procedural atrocity.","start":1026.88,"stop":1031.875,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No it would not, it is…","start":1031.875,"stop":1033.717,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Or a karate chop would not be?","start":1033.717,"stop":1036.8,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"If the karate, I see situations in which the hands can be used as instruments to do as much danger as a paddle.","start":1036.8,"stop":1048.752,"duration":11.95}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"The distinction between injury and pain, would you make any distinction there?","start":1048.752,"stop":1055.274,"duration":6.52}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"I would not focus on injury, or pain, I would focus on punishment, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1055.274,"stop":1059.15,"duration":3.88},{"text":"I don’t want to have to measure afterwards whether or not there was an entitlement to hear and what we are saying is when one is beaten by an instrument there is a right to hearing.","start":1059.15,"stop":1067.714,"duration":8.56},{"text":"I must add that I’m limiting this case to the facts of this case.","start":1067.714,"stop":1071.194,"duration":3.48},{"text":"This case deals with an instrument, it doesn’t deals with karate chops, it doesn’t involve that kind of situation.","start":1071.194,"stop":1076.553,"duration":5.36},{"text":"Let’s go with the limitation you are making on the hands would like to be gently slapped by Mohammad Ali?","start":1076.553,"stop":1086.083,"duration":9.53}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No I would not Mr. Justice Marshall.","start":1086.083,"stop":1088.713,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t think you should limit it, if you want to go there ahead?","start":1088.713,"stop":1094.071,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But your Fourteenth Amendment argument is tied to punishment, just as your Eighth Amendment argument.","start":1094.071,"stop":1099.131,"duration":5.06}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Punishment, yes, down under the color of state law.","start":1099.131,"stop":1102.304,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Any difference in definition, of punishment for your Fourteenth Amendment argument and for punishment in your Eighth Amendment.","start":1102.304,"stop":1108.257,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly because the Eighth Amendment argument is severe and excessive punishment, the 14th Amendment due process argument is punishment which is the punishment which is permissible, even under Florida Law, corporal punishment.","start":1108.257,"stop":1120.856,"duration":12.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Five slaps with a ruler on the hand, it still require a hearing before it could be administered?","start":1120.856,"stop":1126.78,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it would, and let me say this, under the Florida Law the statute in the school board regulations they already require some consultation with the principal, prior to administration of corporal punishment, that kind of corporal punishment.","start":1126.78,"stop":1139.54,"duration":12.76},{"text":"So, the hearing that we are asking for would not be any intrusion really into the public school workings on a daily basis, we submit that there must be a minimal opportunity for a hearing, something similar to Goss versus Lopez and there must be decision is to whether or not the punishment should be administered by a neutral and detached person.","start":1139.54,"stop":1159.269,"duration":19.73},{"text":"The Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit in absolutely precluding Eighth Amendment and Fourteenth Amendment relieve, it seems to us goes much too far.","start":1159.269,"stop":1169.818,"duration":10.55},{"text":"I will reserve the rest of my time for tomorrow morning and rebuttal.","start":1169.818,"stop":1173.937,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We have about eight minutes I think we will let you go ahead Mr. Howard.","start":1173.937,"stop":1185.47,"duration":11.53}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the court.","start":1185.47,"stop":1189.039,"duration":3.57},{"text":"The court is being asked in this case to take two long further steps into still another area of school discipline, public school discipline.","start":1189.039,"stop":1200.772,"duration":11.73},{"text":"The court has been asked to expand the bounds of the Eighth Amendment, as we have understood at least under the decisions of this court to provide Federal actions, whenever a student or a student’s parents perceives that a punishment has been immoderate or unacceptable to the student or the parent.","start":1200.772,"stop":1222.34,"duration":21.57},{"text":"Secondly the court has been asked to mandate constitutional due process procedures in every case of corporal punishment by extension of the rule that the court adopted in Goss versus Lopez, providing for due process in suspension cases up to ten days.","start":1222.34,"stop":1241.373,"duration":19.03},{"text":"We see the case as an opportunity, first for the court to clarify and reaffirm the scope of the Eighth Amendment as been limited to punishments inflicted either as a consequence of or collateral to the criminal process and secondly if not to overrule, Goss versus Lopez at least to confine it within it’s rationale and not to open that rule to threaten the discretion of educators and still more and more and more day to day decisions which are been made throughout the nation in the schools.","start":1241.373,"stop":1285.966,"duration":44.59}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"How do you square that with what the court said in Strickland?","start":1285.966,"stop":1293.384,"duration":7.42},{"text":"If records where now to say the same general procedures provided for Strickland against Wood case would apply here, would that be an extension, or would you regard that as an extension of law.","start":1293.384,"stop":1309.658,"duration":16.27}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I would.","start":1309.658,"stop":1311.559,"duration":1.9},{"text":"See the Wood versus Strickland case as an additional reason for the court not to take yet another step in the due process procedural field because","start":1311.559,"stop":1323.996,"duration":12.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Would that be another step or would it be the same step applied to a different context?","start":1323.996,"stop":1330.443,"duration":6.45}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it would be an another step, Mr. Chief Justice I'm not recalling the specific facts of Wood versus Strickland now as I recall it, it was a suspension case, this is a…","start":1330.443,"stop":1341.059,"duration":10.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"As a matter of very short time as a disciplinary measure, but if any corporal punishment.","start":1341.059,"stop":1350.126,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"I am urging the court to accept the view that corporal punishment is a lesser order of discipline even than suspensions.","start":1350.126,"stop":1361.132,"duration":11.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the first -- you are dealing I suppose, if I understand you, with the procedural due process aspect of this play, of this case but neither Goss or Strickland involved on the Eighth Amendment issue at all.","start":1361.132,"stop":1374.022,"duration":12.89}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true sir, but I agree with counsel that we had a too separate decision.","start":1374.022,"stop":1378.857,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Howard State or Federal in Florida had any restrictions on corporal punishment in the school system?","start":1378.857,"stop":1388.637,"duration":9.78}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"At the time the case arose Mr. Justice the statue in Florida was a very short section which by negative implication, authorized corporal punished in the defining the authority of the teacher.","start":1388.637,"stop":1403.264,"duration":14.63},{"text":"Since that time in fact just this year state legislature has enacted a fairly comprehensive, set of laws dealing with student conduct and it now extensively defines corporal punishment and provides procedures for how it is to be administered.","start":1403.264,"stop":1419.908,"duration":16.64}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But at time this record as I have read it was little bit horrible and it stands uncontradicted because of case in the law and it is (Inaudible) for me to do but they view it that that is possible under Florida law.","start":1419.908,"stop":1438.149,"duration":18.24}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"I could disagree Mr. Justice respectfully that, with your characterization of the record I disagree.","start":1438.149,"stop":1445.142,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"What takes the little fellow hand I think some had this hand.","start":1445.142,"stop":1450.305,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Justice in considering the phrase under any definition cruel unusual.","start":1450.305,"stop":1459.04,"duration":8.73},{"text":"We have in this case – I submit a few incidents of immoderate and even severe if you will punishment.","start":1459.04,"stop":1470.533,"duration":11.49},{"text":"But in the context of what the case sort to establish and the size and variety of the school system and the fact most of the punishments which the record reflect were trivials.","start":1470.533,"stop":1484.484,"duration":13.95},{"text":"I submit to you that the evidence did not come anywhere near showing cruel and unusual punishment, however you may choose to define that and...","start":1484.484,"stop":1495.409,"duration":10.93}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But at that time that teaches could do what ever he you want?","start":1495.409,"stop":1498.887,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir he could not under the…","start":1498.887,"stop":1501.505,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the restriction…?","start":1501.505,"stop":1503.277,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Well there was a Dade County School Board policy ineffective of the time which provided that a teacher must himself with the principal before corporal punishment could be administrated.","start":1503.277,"stop":1517.859,"duration":14.58},{"text":"That punishment should take place in the presence of another adult.","start":1517.859,"stop":1521.568,"duration":3.71},{"text":"Student should be informed of the reasons for the punishment and what the misconduct was.","start":1521.568,"stop":1527.315,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the punishment?","start":1527.315,"stop":1529.889,"duration":2.57},{"text":"There were no restriction on the punishment could he be paddle 125 times?","start":1529.889,"stop":1536.359,"duration":6.47}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"There were no explicit restrictions except statements that it must be -- it must not exceed reasonable moderate bounds which has been the common law definition I understand it.","start":1536.359,"stop":1547.945,"duration":11.59},{"text":"The best test of the record I might say Mr. Justice is the district judge who is the man, the court most of the position to assess the facts, dismiss this case at the close of the plaintiff’s evidence and use the plaintiff’s test, he accepted the standards of the Eighth Amendment did apply and found that the facts did not rise to that level.","start":1547.945,"stop":1576.652,"duration":28.71},{"text":"Coming then to the Eighth Amendment issue, the issue as we see it is simply whether or not the amendments applies at all.","start":1576.652,"stop":1586.473,"duration":9.82},{"text":"The Fifth Circuit in this case, the en banc court held that it did not and gave some careful analysis to the history and the rationality of the amendment.","start":1586.473,"stop":1599.763,"duration":13.29},{"text":"One circuit disagrees the Eighth Circuit has held in a case that went only on the pleadings that the Eighth Amendment can apply there was no analysis, no reasoning to support the conclusion.","start":1599.763,"stop":1612.872,"duration":13.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Howard suppose there were two inmates in a mental institution, one was there because of the criminal commitment, the other one was there because of the civil commitment in the same institution.","start":1612.872,"stop":1627.016,"duration":14.14},{"text":"Would the Eighth Amendment apply to one not to the other?","start":1627.016,"stop":1631.837,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice I am aware of the Jackson versus Bishop case of course, I would say first with respect that this court has never gone so far as to say that punishments even to prisoners violates the Eighth Amendment.","start":1631.837,"stop":1651.528,"duration":19.69},{"text":"Now I must say that I don’t have a lot of doubt what the outcome that is might be.","start":1651.528,"stop":1662.187,"duration":10.66}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel I think we will resume that in the afternoon.","start":1662.187,"stop":1666.229,"duration":4.04}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 03, 1976","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger6/oral_argument_audio/17618","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will resume the arguments in number 6527.","start":0,"stop":9.775,"duration":9.78},{"text":"Mr. Howard, you have 22 minutes remaining.","start":9.775,"stop":14.972,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the court.","start":14.972,"stop":18.831,"duration":3.86},{"text":"When the court recessed yesterday, I was attempting to answer Mr. Justice Blackmun’s question which I understood to be whether civilly committed institutional inmates were within the reach of the Eighth Amendment.","start":18.831,"stop":35.125,"duration":16.29},{"text":"I would like to try to arrive at the answer by explaining our theory of the reach of the Eighth Amendment, and why under that theory derived from this court’s decisions, my answer to the question would have to be no.","start":35.125,"stop":53.041,"duration":17.92},{"text":"This court’s decisions have never, in my reading, departed from the historic intent or the literal tax to the amendment which is internally consistent.","start":53.041,"stop":65.131,"duration":12.09},{"text":"It speaks of excessive fines, excessive bails, and cruel and unusual punishments.","start":65.131,"stop":72.896,"duration":7.77},{"text":"The amendment, as we read the court’s decisions, only speaks to punishments which are inflected consequential to or collateral to the criminal process of law.","start":72.896,"stop":85.558,"duration":12.66},{"text":"Corporal punishment in the schools, in our view is no part of the criminal process by any view.","start":85.558,"stop":92.694,"duration":7.14},{"text":"It is civil and correctional therapeutic in nature.","start":92.694,"stop":97.086,"duration":4.39},{"text":"It is not within the criminal concepts at all.","start":97.086,"stop":101.949,"duration":4.86},{"text":"The history of the Eight Amendment has been explained too often for me to try to bore the court with it.","start":101.949,"stop":108.989,"duration":7.04},{"text":"It originated from the imposition of inhumane sentences by the English Courts.","start":108.989,"stop":116.165,"duration":7.18},{"text":"Its interpretation by this Court’s decisions, as uniformly have been in the criminal context.","start":116.165,"stop":122.842,"duration":6.68},{"text":"In fact, the court has rejected his application in civil cases, in such cases as the deportation, the Fong Yue Ting case, and in a case involving Incarceration for Civil Contempt.","start":122.842,"stop":136.811,"duration":13.97},{"text":"This court has rejected the Eight Amendment as applicable there to give relief.","start":136.811,"stop":142.594,"duration":5.78},{"text":"The clearest illustration, we believe is in the case which is heavily relied upon by the petitioners and that is Trop v. Dulles.","start":142.594,"stop":151.943,"duration":9.35},{"text":"The distinction can be seen by comparing Trop with its companion case which was decided by this court on the same day in 1958, Perez v. Brownell.","start":151.943,"stop":162.635,"duration":10.69},{"text":"The Nationality Act of 1940 in Perez, stripped Mr. Perez of his citizenship because he voted in a foreign election.","start":162.635,"stop":172.838,"duration":10.2},{"text":"There was no criminal conviction, there was no criminal process.","start":172.838,"stop":176.459,"duration":3.62},{"text":"The court sustain that denationalization.","start":176.459,"stop":181.107,"duration":4.65},{"text":"In Trop, Mr. Trop had been found guilty by Court Marshall at wartime desertion and the statute there imposed denationalization as a consequence of that conviction.","start":181.107,"stop":195.54,"duration":14.43},{"text":"Chief Justice Warren in the opinion, as we read the opinion, only came to the question of the Eight Amendment, after finding that there was a conviction.","start":195.54,"stop":206.002,"duration":10.46},{"text":"The Eight Amendment was invoked by that criminal consequence.","start":206.002,"stop":211.838,"duration":5.84},{"text":"He then preceded to the famous language about penal and the distinction between penal and non-penal statutes, that the government cannot label something non-penal, when it is really penal.","start":211.838,"stop":224.821,"duration":12.98},{"text":"In our view, that is a secondary test, the threshold test is always whether there is a criminal process in link or nexus.","start":224.821,"stop":234.674,"duration":9.85},{"text":"If there is found such a connection then the question is whether the punishment is penal and if it found to be penal then the question is, is it cruel and unusual and, the court has certainly expanded the definition of the term cruel and unusual but we submit that it has never expanded the basic definition of punishment.","start":234.674,"stop":258.692,"duration":24.02},{"text":"So, unless there is punishment in the Eight Amendment sentence, the amendment does not apply and that brings me to the cases in the lower courts which have departed from this standard that I am suggesting.","start":258.692,"stop":272.967,"duration":14.27},{"text":"The prison cases are the best example and the most famous prison case is that decision written by Mr. Justice Blackmun, while on the Court of Appeals, Jackson v. Bishop in which the flogging of prisoners in Arkansas Penitentiaries was prohibited as violated the Eight Amendment.","start":272.967,"stop":296.666,"duration":23.7},{"text":"Other cases have applied it into juvenile institutions, the Nelson v. Heyne in the Seventh Circuit, dealt with a juvenile institution where there criminal and non-criminal youngsters in the institution but it gave no analysis to what we see to be the threshold issue.","start":296.666,"stop":321.426,"duration":24.76}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Howard, can I interrupt?","start":321.426,"stop":323.001,"duration":1.57},{"text":"I cannot remember whether yesterday, you answered Mr. Justice Blackmun’s question about two persons in the same institution.","start":323.001,"stop":329.238,"duration":6.24},{"text":"One, there is resolved of conviction for crime and the other is finding of mental illness, and the same punishment being meted out to both, it was if your answer, that one would have Eighth Amendment Claim and the other would not?","start":329.238,"stop":340.476,"duration":11.24}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, I was really trying in a long way to get that answer now by explaining our theory.","start":340.476,"stop":345.724,"duration":5.25},{"text":"My answer would be yes, that under rigorous analysis of this court’s decisions, the civilly committed mental patient would not have benefit of the Eight Amendment.","start":345.724,"stop":356.967,"duration":11.24}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Would your analysis be the same if both of them, if the person inflicting the discipline, said in words, this is punishment and was doing what was in effect, punishing the man for a kind of both situation.","start":356.967,"stop":370.473,"duration":13.51}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I would be the same Mr. Justice.","start":370.473,"stop":373.337,"duration":2.86},{"text":"Again, I see it as a question of contours of the Eighth Amendment and what I see to be a blurring of those contours by lower court treatment, so far which has not examined this problem.","start":373.337,"stop":388.348,"duration":15.01},{"text":"Most of the cases involving mixed institutional custody have not stated why the Eight Amendment is invoked.","start":388.348,"stop":399.117,"duration":10.77},{"text":"They have assumed that it has been invoked.","start":399.117,"stop":401.569,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"I was wondering if one could reconcile the case as you described about the loss of citizenship, by simply saying that one case it was punishment and the other case, it was not, rather than saying in one case there was a criminal process and the other was not.","start":401.569,"stop":414.484,"duration":12.91},{"text":"Wouldn’t the opinions be consistent with that rather simple approach, or is any language in the opinions, that would be inconsistent with that rather simple approach?","start":414.484,"stop":423.561,"duration":9.08}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I have am find it difficult to see the analogy, Mr. Justice Stevens because in the Perez and Trop cases, the end result was exactly the same and the only distinction that I can see between taking away -- restoring Mr. Trop’s citizenship when he was convicted of wartime desertion and taking away from Mr. Perez when he voted in a foreign election was the Chief Justice’s lead in the opinion by discussing punishment as a consequence of crime.","start":423.561,"stop":459.128,"duration":35.57}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But couldn't one just simply say punishment, and forget it as a consequence of crime, wouldn’t the same distinction apply?","start":459.128,"stop":464.281,"duration":5.15},{"text":"That is really my problem.","start":464.281,"stop":467.483,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Sir.","start":467.483,"stop":469.312,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"As in the loss of citizenship situation, it clearly was, I mean, in the consequence of wartime desertion, it was clearly punishment.","start":469.312,"stop":477.333,"duration":8.02},{"text":"It seemed to me, if that had been done by executive order or by some other procedure, other than it, results a crime, one could consistently with the opinion still call it punishment covered by Eight Amendment.","start":477.333,"stop":488.04,"duration":10.71},{"text":"I am not quite sure why one could not do that.","start":488.04,"stop":490.085,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But it followed a Court Marshall conviction for a criminal offense, didn’t it?","start":490.085,"stop":493.84,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is clearly did.","start":493.84,"stop":494.759,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Not only that.","start":494.759,"stop":495.754,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"And, I believe that was Chief Justice Warren’s basis for reaching the Eighth Amendment.","start":495.754,"stop":501.659,"duration":5.9},{"text":"He did not articulate the reasoning that I am urging to the court.","start":501.659,"stop":507.049,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that is my point, the opinion does not articulate the rationale what you find in the opinion.","start":507.049,"stop":511.322,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in so many words but I think, the rationale is there and has to be recognized.","start":511.322,"stop":518.07,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Howard on your two men in the mental institution, how do you get around the screws case?","start":518.07,"stop":526.464,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir, I.","start":526.464,"stop":527.359,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They were both -- both of them are incarcerated.","start":527.359,"stop":531.133,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, I would not accept that.","start":531.133,"stop":535.021,"duration":3.89},{"text":"I would say that it is --","start":535.021,"stop":535.522,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"A confident, civilly committed man and say, “You did some wrong, you spit on the floor and so I am going deny you, your rights and I am going to beat daylights out of you, punish you.”","start":535.522,"stop":548.463,"duration":12.94}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice, I..","start":548.463,"stop":549.153,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Did I not screw?","start":549.153,"stop":551.465,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I do not think they are the same.","start":551.465,"stop":554.113,"duration":2.65},{"text":"I think that the courts have had a solicitor for institutional cases and it is perfectly understandable when a man’s or a child’s liberty is taken away from him and he is put in into an institution and he is isolated from the community.","start":554.113,"stop":572.357,"duration":18.24},{"text":"And, he cannot go home to his parents at night and he is subjected to inhumane conditions in that institution, then the courts have found that the conditions demand a remedy.”","start":572.357,"stop":584.786,"duration":12.43},{"text":"I would suggest that the Fourteenth Amendment would be more appropriate as a remedy in those situations in the Eight Amendment.","start":584.786,"stop":592.747,"duration":7.96},{"text":"And, a few courts have drawn that distinction between the prisoners either in jail or in a reformatory as a result of a criminal act and inmates there, either because of mental incompetence or because they are pre-trial detainees, it seems to me that for a detainee or a mental patient to suffer inhumane treatment or conditions is so irrationally and so unrelated to a state objective that he could challenge that treatment based on Fourteenth Amendment.","start":592.747,"stop":626.137,"duration":33.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You said, it is only not fairly a violation of Eighth Amendment, you are not saying it could be a violation.","start":626.137,"stop":630.741,"duration":4.6}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not saying that there could not be a remedy and of course, if we take it to this case, that is the issue that is not before the court today.","start":630.741,"stop":639.583,"duration":8.84},{"text":"There was a third question presented in the petition for Certiorari which would have brought a substitute for Due Process issue here.","start":639.583,"stop":648.963,"duration":9.38},{"text":"And, the court did not accept that and of course, neither of us have briefed it and I would not want to make any concessions on it but that is a possibility.","start":648.963,"stop":660.094,"duration":11.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But your point, as I understand it is, the screws case involved a deprivation of life without Due Process of law and did not involve the Eighth Amendment as said.","start":660.094,"stop":672.316,"duration":12.22}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":672.316,"stop":673.172,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It fairly expert who argue the screws case.","start":673.172,"stop":677.453,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"The screws case, of course, was a criminal case and it required specific intent but I think this gets us back to the case that was argued yesterday but the right has to be found if there is to be a deprivation.","start":677.453,"stop":692.511,"duration":15.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Howard could I interrupt again, it seems to me, we may just be arguing what constitutional basis there would be for the kind of review the plaintiff seeks in this case, because, if I understand you correctly, you are saying that if the student is given a fair hearing, say, they have a full trial on whatever the charge against him is and a fair procedure to determine his guilt.","start":692.511,"stop":713.966,"duration":21.46},{"text":"And, then as a result of that they impose a punishment so, they decide this offence justifies locking him in the basement for four days or something, in the basement of the school without bread or water or anything.","start":713.966,"stop":723.967,"duration":10},{"text":"I think, you are saying as a matter of Substantive Due Process, that would be intolerable even though it might not violate the Eighth Amendment and, if so, what difference does it really make?","start":723.967,"stop":732.546,"duration":8.58},{"text":"(Inaudible) is going to be one of it and such an extremely severe penalty as related to the offence, that it is not constitutionally tolerable.","start":732.546,"stop":740.573,"duration":8.03}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice, I think there are several questions that I do not wish to conceive that there is a Fourteenth Amendment substantive remedy here because we really have it examined or briefed in, and certainly I do not conceive that Procedural Due Process steps are required in every case.","start":740.573,"stop":760.747,"duration":20.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but I am assuming, we give the Procedural Due Process to get that aspect out of the questions that is all.","start":760.747,"stop":765.755,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"And, then I have a punishment.","start":765.755,"stop":767.255,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Then say you locked a 5-year-old or 7-year-old boy in the basement for ten days.","start":767.255,"stop":773.2,"duration":5.95},{"text":"Could a school do that, provided you gave him an adequate hearing, would the constitution tolerate that?","start":773.2,"stop":778.028,"duration":4.83},{"text":"I think your position is either yes or it has to be under some provision other than the Eighth Amendment.","start":778.028,"stop":785.988,"duration":7.96}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly, the schools cannot do it.","start":785.988,"stop":788.434,"duration":2.45},{"text":"My first position would be that there are adequate enough state remedies and no reasons to suspect that those remedies are not being enforced that there is no clear call for federal...","start":788.434,"stop":801.535,"duration":13.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How can you acknowledge the state right to do that and yet question the hypothetical case about the inmate in a mental institution who has given unusually severe discipline?","start":801.535,"stop":810.18,"duration":8.64},{"text":"What is the difference in constitutional terms?","start":810.18,"stop":813.629,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I maybe have driven to the point of relaying, falling back on the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":813.629,"stop":822.27,"duration":8.64},{"text":"I find it is difficult to say that a student who suffers truly excessive punishment cannot have any remedy.","start":822.27,"stop":831.683,"duration":9.41},{"text":"But I...","start":831.683,"stop":832.473,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you prefer to have us find it a matter of Substantive Due Process rather than apply the Eight Amendment?","start":832.473,"stop":837.497,"duration":5.02}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"I would prefer Mr. Justice that it come to you in an appropriate case so that the question can be examined very carefully and I wish only to make.","start":837.497,"stop":847.071,"duration":9.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that the very issue here?","start":847.071,"stop":848.791,"duration":1.72},{"text":"Whether no matter how severe the punishment, there is any constitutional remedy based on the facts alleged here.","start":848.791,"stop":854.596,"duration":5.8},{"text":"Maybe he has proceeded under the wrong theory but do you still deny him any relief?","start":854.596,"stop":858.247,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the only issue that the court faces here with respect to severe punishment is whether the Eighth Amendment reaches in.","start":858.247,"stop":866.856,"duration":8.61},{"text":"It was -- the Fourteenth Amendment was a part of the case below.","start":866.856,"stop":872.008,"duration":5.15},{"text":"The Fifth Circuit, for example, rejected an examination case by case of the punishments inflicted in this case and I think at least partly on the theory that it gets the Federal Courts squarely into the business of second-guessing school administrators as to whether proper punishment was necessary and if it was then whether to two licks or swats what or five licks was appropriate in each case.","start":872.008,"stop":901.51,"duration":29.5},{"text":"I think the Fifth Circuit held that that was not an appropriate function of the Federal Courts and I would refer to your language in Bishop v. Wood, the case involving the dismissal of the City employee in which you made the point that the Federal Courts and not the appropriate forms to pass on daily multitudinous decisions which were handed down everyday in public agencies.","start":901.51,"stop":932.897,"duration":31.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Which do not affect litigants’ constitutional rights but here I am troubled by the problem, and see the underlying problem here is whether the constitution protects an individual from being in prison indefinitely by a school.","start":932.897,"stop":946.694,"duration":13.8},{"text":"If that is the course, the school chooses to punish.","start":946.694,"stop":950.303,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Here there was no imprisonment.","start":950.303,"stop":951.441,"duration":1.14},{"text":"There was no deprivation of liberty, was it there?","start":951.441,"stop":953.319,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but, in principle it is the same thing, at least...","start":953.319,"stop":955.18,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but not in the constitution which -- under the Fourteenth and the Fifteenth Amendment talks about life, liberty or property, and, here there was no deprivation of --","start":955.18,"stop":964.231,"duration":9.05}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there was not and -- the ordinary case, of course, involves a temporary detention and no deprivation of liberty.","start":964.231,"stop":972.426,"duration":8.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But the point would be, the only constitutional protection against the deprivation of liberty is to have the procedural due process preceded.","start":972.426,"stop":978.885,"duration":6.46},{"text":"And, I am assuming that the deprivation of liberty that I described was made only after a fair and full trial as retaining guilt.","start":978.885,"stop":985.926,"duration":7.04},{"text":"The question is, is there any limit on the punishment the state can impose on the student for as in correction of the school rule and I found in your position is, there is no limit unless it is substantive to some kind of Substantive Due Process.","start":985.926,"stop":998.75,"duration":12.82}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"I find it very difficult to take the extreme position that you put me in Mr. Justice and I only it again that I would urged court.","start":998.75,"stop":1005.741,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it not the problem with the Fifth Circuit opinion?","start":1005.741,"stop":1008.381,"duration":2.64},{"text":"We do not have to review every time a student gets slapped in order to avoid the constitutional extreme that the Fifth Circuit has reached, that is the only suggestion I am making.","start":1008.381,"stop":1017.218,"duration":8.84}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I had may have to do also with this dilemma of what right in the constitution is secured?","start":1017.218,"stop":1024.347,"duration":7.13},{"text":"Now, if the Eight Amendment does not cover it, does the Fourteenth Amendment by its own force and the fact provide that right?","start":1024.347,"stop":1032.387,"duration":8.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that question was presented at the petition, was it not and service was not granted on that issue.","start":1032.387,"stop":1037.906,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"It was not granted, Your Honor and that is why..","start":1037.906,"stop":1040.319,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The limit of the grant is questions one and two?","start":1040.319,"stop":1042.883,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, I am urging the court not to rush to judgment on this unless the case comes to you with called full briefs and argument because..","start":1042.883,"stop":1053.815,"duration":10.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Whereas, we are along the line is that the teacher struck this child up on the street.","start":1053.815,"stop":1060.341,"duration":6.53},{"text":"That would be assault and battery, wouldn't it?","start":1060.341,"stop":1064.256,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir and..","start":1064.256,"stop":1066.293,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But, maybe because it is in the school that it takes it out of the assault and battery.","start":1066.293,"stop":1072.94,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I do not think it does.","start":1072.94,"stop":1076.664,"duration":3.72},{"text":"I think that these are essentially as the Fifth Circuit stated, Tort claims.","start":1076.664,"stop":1082.962,"duration":6.3},{"text":"The constitution does not provide a remedy for every wrong and Section 1983 as Paul v. Davis teaches us.","start":1082.962,"stop":1092.516,"duration":9.55}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That assault matter is obviously the state, it is not a federal.","start":1092.516,"stop":1095.405,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Frank A. Howard","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Sir, one of the judges on the Court of Appeals asked counsel during the argument, is this not an attempt to use a constitutional cannon to kill Florida, do away with the Florida flyspeck and it seems to me that was an apt question.","start":1095.405,"stop":1112.931,"duration":17.53},{"text":"If I might turn to the due process issue, I understood Mr. Rogow yesterday to concede the point that we make in our brief and that is that the true issue here is whether procedural due process steps are required before the administration of any punishment, not just severe.","start":1112.931,"stop":1136.008,"duration":23.08},{"text":"I would prefer to quarrel with his definition but I do not believe I have to.","start":1136.008,"stop":1140.794,"duration":4.79},{"text":"This theory has been rejected by all courts which have considered it, with the exception of Baker v. Owen in which this court held that parental objection may not overruled the administrator's discretion.","start":1140.794,"stop":1156.81,"duration":16.02},{"text":"The court did not review the question of Procedural Due Process or it was a precedent there.","start":1156.81,"stop":1162.142,"duration":5.33},{"text":"The Baker Court found a few steps to be a necessary and there is one unreported cases from Georgia which he has cited in the briefs, which also required a...","start":1162.142,"stop":1173.288,"duration":11.15},{"text":"Goss v. Lopez is the starting point, we believe here, and the Goss case as we see it was predicated upon the deprivation of the right to education.","start":1173.288,"stop":1185.088,"duration":11.8},{"text":"That suspensions at least took the child out of school, away from the education which the state had guarantied to give them.","start":1185.088,"stop":1195.089,"duration":10},{"text":"Corporal punishment in contrast is correction while keeping the child in school.","start":1195.089,"stop":1200.036,"duration":4.95},{"text":"The purpose of Corporal Punishment as a disciplinary alternative, is to correct the child quickly while putting him back to class.","start":1200.036,"stop":1208.935,"duration":8.9},{"text":"The record here at least shows there was no retardation of progress of any of the children.","start":1208.935,"stop":1215.735,"duration":6.8},{"text":"The numerous citations are collected in brief to the record, the students progressed fairly, and normally on through school.","start":1215.735,"stop":1224.886,"duration":9.15},{"text":"They suffered no reputational harm and there is no showing that future schooling or future employment was jeopardized.","start":1224.886,"stop":1234.557,"duration":9.67},{"text":"So, in so far as the, in the first inquiry whether there is a protected interest, the state of Florida guarantees children the right to an education but it does not guarantee them the right to go public school with immunity from corporal punishment in case of misconduct.","start":1234.557,"stop":1257.003,"duration":22.45},{"text":"The petitioners have sought to find a secured right in the Fourth Amendment for which there is no case support at all and it was never argued below, Fourth Circuit did not even deal with this question.","start":1257.003,"stop":1270.17,"duration":13.17},{"text":"Mr. Rogow suggested the number theory and I do not know how far that goes or what it covers.","start":1270.17,"stop":1277.937,"duration":7.77},{"text":"Further, I think and his most strongest reliance is on some generalized liberty interest.","start":1277.937,"stop":1286.556,"duration":8.62},{"text":"We say first that there is no deprivation of liberty.","start":1286.556,"stop":1292.767,"duration":6.21},{"text":"The constitution says that liberty shall not be deprived or taken away and Corporal Punishment in the normal situation, and that is what we are talking about, is a temporary detention only for correctional purposes.","start":1292.767,"stop":1308.148,"duration":15.38},{"text":"The student’s liberty interest is just one ingredient and a balance of interest which is then reached by the states, by almost all of the states.","start":1308.148,"stop":1318,"duration":9.85},{"text":"State policy and history, in this country, favor local educators, discretion and control in these sorts of decisions and provide remedies when that discretion is abused.","start":1318,"stop":1331.738,"duration":13.74},{"text":"So, we submit that there is no fall for a federal mold which is going to be frightening to administrators, probably self-defeating in terms of the use of this remedy.","start":1331.738,"stop":1346.454,"duration":14.72},{"text":"Because educators do not look upon rules of the Supreme Court even if they are called informal.","start":1346.454,"stop":1352.481,"duration":6.03},{"text":"They do not look upon them as informal.","start":1352.481,"stop":1355.713,"duration":3.23},{"text":"They are mindful of Wood v. Strickland, the personal liability problem, and my time is up and I thank you for it.","start":1355.713,"stop":1364.855,"duration":9.14}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Howard.","start":1364.855,"stop":1367.337,"duration":2.48},{"text":"Mr. Rogow do you have anything further.","start":1367.337,"stop":1370.092,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"I do Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1370.092,"stop":1373.461,"duration":3.37},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the court.","start":1373.461,"stop":1377.106,"duration":3.64},{"text":"As I understand Mr. Howard’s argument, it boils down to the fact that the constitution can ban the flogging of prisoners but it cannot ban the flogging of students.","start":1377.106,"stop":1391.8,"duration":14.69},{"text":"We do not think that..","start":1391.8,"stop":1393.077,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He was arguing that --","start":1393.077,"stop":1394.546,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"He was limiting his remark of the Eighth Amendments.","start":1394.546,"stop":1397.158,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and so am I at this point, Mr. Justice White and I want to reiterate to the court that there are two separate and distinct issues in this case.","start":1397.158,"stop":1404.23,"duration":7.07},{"text":"In the Eighth Amendment context, the argument is that this punishment is civil in nature and not criminal and, therefore some distinction can be drawn on that basis, so, it is merely a label of convenience.","start":1404.23,"stop":1416.784,"duration":12.55},{"text":"The factor to be looked at is whether or not it is punishment, irrespective of who is meeting out that punishment.","start":1416.784,"stop":1423.94,"duration":7.16},{"text":"In Trop v. Dulles and Perez v. Brownell, when one reads them, I think one sees that the focus is upon punishment.","start":1423.94,"stop":1432.915,"duration":8.97},{"text":"Not punishment for a crime but whether or not there was punishment involved and the court found in Perez that stripping a person of his nationality was not punishment.","start":1432.915,"stop":1444.176,"duration":11.26},{"text":"What it was, was an exercise of international affairs power of Congress saying that if someone voted in a foreign election then, because we had to show the foreign country, that we were not interfering in their business, we would strip a person of his nationality but it was not at all looking at that as punishment.","start":1444.176,"stop":1464.327,"duration":20.15},{"text":"In Trop, it was punishment and so the focus is upon punishment, I think that is important.","start":1464.327,"stop":1468.656,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it was precisely the same thing in both Trop and in Perez, i.e. the deprivation of citizenship.","start":1468.656,"stop":1476.291,"duration":7.63},{"text":"And, the reason it was punishment in the one case, in Trop, and not punishment in Perez is one, I had understood or one could understand was that in Trop, it followed a conviction of a criminal offence.","start":1476.291,"stop":1491.143,"duration":14.85},{"text":"And, isn't that what made it punishment.","start":1491.143,"stop":1493.383,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I do not --","start":1493.383,"stop":1493.839,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Let us say, it was part of the sanction imposed upon one convicted of criminal offence and in the other case there was no criminal proceeding whatsoever.","start":1493.839,"stop":1503.4,"duration":9.56},{"text":"Now, isn’t that what made the same consequence, punishment in the one case and not punishment in the other.","start":1503.4,"stop":1509.78,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Mr. Justice Stewart, at the way, I read it, when one reads Perez carefully, one notes that the original law which stripped a person of his nationality, which was a civil law -- a civil war involved no desertion, conviction at all.","start":1509.78,"stop":1523.924,"duration":14.14},{"text":"The historical basis for Trop and Perez was an old statute that said, “If you served or if you are deserted, whether you are convicted or not, you would be stripped of your nationality.”","start":1523.924,"stop":1533.714,"duration":9.79},{"text":"I think the focus is upon punishment.","start":1533.714,"stop":1535.496,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Why was it punishment in the one case and not in the other?","start":1535.496,"stop":1538.159,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Because...","start":1538.159,"stop":1538.679,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"They precise same thing.","start":1538.679,"stop":1540.542,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Because in Perez, it was not punishment because Congress was exercising a specific power that it had, not to punish a person but to protect the country and I think, when one reads Perez carefully, that that is a conclusion that one comes to, that is the basis for the distinction.","start":1540.542,"stop":1557.652,"duration":17.11},{"text":"I do not think it make very much difference to our case, quite frankly.","start":1557.652,"stop":1561.018,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But what if Congress says, we exercised an interstate commerce power here and that we are going to do this too, does that make it not punishment, if Congress is exercising a specific power?","start":1561.018,"stop":1571.252,"duration":10.23}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"If it is an illegitimate exercise of that power which it was in Perez and there was a legitimate governmental interest that was being protected and the Court found that in Perez.","start":1571.252,"stop":1579.914,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But, I thought the Cruel And Unusual Punishment Clause was a barrier to what would otherwise be a quite sweeping exercise of Congressional power, that you have the power to regulate interstate commerce, almost anyway you want to, except when you run against specific prohibition, the Bill of Right, or are you saying that that is not the case?","start":1579.914,"stop":1599.881,"duration":19.97}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I am not saying that is not the case but I am saying that the first question that must be addressed is whether or not the intent of Congress in inflicting some kind of a sanction upon a person is to punish.","start":1599.881,"stop":1613.19,"duration":13.31}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the source of Congressional power is not really relevant here.","start":1613.19,"stop":1617.537,"duration":4.35},{"text":"Is it so long as it so, one might inquire upon whether or not it was an appropriate exercise of power granted by the constitution to the Federal legislature, but, once one found an affirmative answer to that, then the question is, did Congress enact a criminal law or a civil law?","start":1617.537,"stop":1634.787,"duration":17.25},{"text":"Congress has enacted many criminal laws under its commerce power, the Dyer Act, the Mann Act, and many, many others.","start":1634.787,"stop":1641.51,"duration":6.72},{"text":"Now, I suppose, and it is enacted as we both know many, many kinds of civil legislation under its commerce power.","start":1641.51,"stop":1648.944,"duration":7.43},{"text":"But, the question is not the source of Congressional power but whether or not this is, what has been created as a criminal offence followed both by criminal sanction, if so, is punishment, and if it is not, it is not.","start":1648.944,"stop":1662.683,"duration":13.74}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Where we disagree Mr. Justice Stewart is that, I do not think that the criminal aspect is important, the punishment aspect is important but as I say, Trop and Perez are not essential to our case at all because we come down to...","start":1662.683,"stop":1674.741,"duration":12.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rogow, in Perez, was there any rule against voting in a foreign election?","start":1674.741,"stop":1680.221,"duration":5.48}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Any rule in what, in the foreign country or in this court...","start":1680.221,"stop":1681.88,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, here.","start":1681.88,"stop":1683.464,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I do not think, I do not think there was...","start":1683.464,"stop":1685.791,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"There was a consequence that was imposed but you violated no law in voting them.","start":1685.791,"stop":1691.705,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1691.705,"stop":1692.097,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But you did by deserting?","start":1692.097,"stop":1694.506,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1694.506,"stop":1696.673,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And in Trop, the suction of expatriation followed only upon conviction of a criminal offence.","start":1696.673,"stop":1704.359,"duration":7.69},{"text":"I am not talking about its predecessor in the Civil War, I am talking about the law involved in Trop, isn't that correct?","start":1704.359,"stop":1708.65,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it did.","start":1708.65,"stop":1709.385,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Not upon the fact of desertion.","start":1709.385,"stop":1710.859,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1710.859,"stop":1711.108,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But upon a conviction of a criminal offence.","start":1711.108,"stop":1713.557,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"All, I am saying is the focus is punishment and must is a punishment, if it is punishment, no matter who meets it out, it can violate the Eighth Amendment.","start":1713.557,"stop":1719.953,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't there some substance in arguing and making you punishment argument that whatever happens to him follows upon the breach -- supposedly follows upon a breach of rule, of an official rule.","start":1719.953,"stop":1733.154,"duration":13.2}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"And, that is exactly what happened in this situation, there are breach in the official rules and then punishment is imposed.","start":1733.154,"stop":1739.966,"duration":6.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What happens if the Principal tells the teacher, \"you have been late three days this week, give me a rule and I will walk you out\", is that a violation of Eighth Amendment?","start":1739.966,"stop":1750.963,"duration":11}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, and we have never said that one whack is a violation of the Eighth Amendment.","start":1750.963,"stop":1754.37,"duration":3.41},{"text":"The question is whether or not, there is some opportunity for hearing before authorized punishment can be imposed.","start":1754.37,"stop":1758.893,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no hearing, there is no nothing, I gave you all the facts.","start":1758.893,"stop":1761.873,"duration":2.98},{"text":"The Principal says, “You have been late, you have been late too many times and you deserve punishment, I am going to punish you, Give me the rule, Why?","start":1761.873,"stop":1769.663,"duration":7.79}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say there should be an opportunity for hearing under the Fourteenth Amendment because..","start":1769.663,"stop":1774.579,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"As per that, a violation of the Eighth Amendment?","start":1774.579,"stop":1776.792,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No Sir, it is not a violation of the Eighth Amendment.","start":1776.792,"stop":1778.324,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The difference between that and this case is...","start":1778.324,"stop":1781.094,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"It is the excessive and severe and brutal nature of the punishment which is imposed.","start":1781.094,"stop":1785.364,"duration":4.27},{"text":"I have said that we are seeking to outlaw under Eighth Amendment concepts, corporal punishment.","start":1785.364,"stop":1790.557,"duration":5.19}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"You said punishment was the key.","start":1790.557,"stop":1792.338,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, first, one looks at punishment.","start":1792.338,"stop":1794.495,"duration":2.16},{"text":"If the punishment is excessive or severe, the Eighth Amendment may come in to play, that is our Eight Amendment argument.","start":1794.495,"stop":1800.097,"duration":5.6},{"text":"In the Fourteenth Amendment context, one looks at punishment again.","start":1800.097,"stop":1802.912,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Was the Fourteenth Amendments here?","start":1802.912,"stop":1804.77,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"The due process argument.","start":1804.77,"stop":1806.636,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Is here?","start":1806.636,"stop":1807.4,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly, if there is punishment that is to be imposed, what we are saying is that there must be an opportunity for hearing prior to the imposition of that punishment because there is both a liberty interest which I talked about yesterday and a property interest which I want to be very clear on, is also involved here.","start":1807.4,"stop":1825.085,"duration":17.68},{"text":"James Ingram was driven from that school by the panel for over a week, had he been suspended for over a week, he would have been entitled to a hearing under Goss v. Lopez.","start":1825.085,"stop":1833.642,"duration":8.56},{"text":"He was in effect, suspended by the panel, so we have a property interest that is involved in addition to a liberty interest.","start":1833.642,"stop":1841.675,"duration":8.03},{"text":"One of the argument that has been raised..","start":1841.675,"stop":1843.364,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But, it did not have the property interest involved in every case in which you contend procedural due process is required.","start":1843.364,"stop":1849.569,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1849.569,"stop":1850.162,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"As most cases would not involve school absence?","start":1850.162,"stop":1852.761,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, another argument that has been raised here is that these are matters that should be left to the public schools.","start":1852.761,"stop":1864.099,"duration":11.34},{"text":"We give wide latitude to the public schools in our argument, but, there come moments when arbitrary decisions by governmental officers bring the constitution into play.","start":1864.099,"stop":1875.222,"duration":11.12},{"text":"Here the due process hearings that we ask serve as a protection.","start":1875.222,"stop":1879.096,"duration":3.87},{"text":"It provides rule by law and not rule by fear, protection of individual against arbitrary action by the government.","start":1879.096,"stop":1885.453,"duration":6.36},{"text":"These did not occur, these kinds of protections did not occur in this case.","start":1885.453,"stop":1890.147,"duration":4.69},{"text":"There was no consultation with the Principal and every if they were consultations with the Principal under Florida Law, there is no opportunity to be heard prior to the infliction of any corporal punishment and, we are saying that there are severe deprivations that are involved and therefore there must be an opportunity to be heard.","start":1890.147,"stop":1908.716,"duration":18.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, judging by your answer to Justice Marshall's question, a severe deprivation would not be necessary.","start":1908.716,"stop":1913.79,"duration":5.07},{"text":"If he is entitled to a hearing before he has one whack with the ruler.","start":1913.79,"stop":1917.352,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I am saying that in a Fourteenth Amendment context, that is a deprivation of liberty because it involves an intrusion, a bodily intrusion, the deprivation of privacy, the result and as the District Court judge found psychological harm, stigma, ridicule, all of that and the facts of this case support that.","start":1917.352,"stop":1934.64,"duration":17.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But, one whack with the ruler is a deprivation of privacy?","start":1934.64,"stop":1938.327,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly is innovation upon one's privacy and freedom, not to be, to have one's bodily integrity invaded by the government.","start":1938.327,"stop":1945.883,"duration":7.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Not to be whacked.","start":1945.883,"stop":1947.836,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Not to be whacked.","start":1947.836,"stop":1949.222,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rogow, I think you agreed yesterday that that would be Tort Action on the Florida Law against the Principal and teacher involved.","start":1949.222,"stop":1960.43,"duration":11.21},{"text":"Is there any reason to think that that would not afford equally and adequate relief to the individuals and questions?","start":1960.43,"stop":1968.062,"duration":7.63}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"It might afford equally adequate relief but Monroe v. Pape says that is not the test.","start":1968.062,"stop":1972.263,"duration":4.2},{"text":"If there is..","start":1972.263,"stop":1972.64,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that, I was asking whether or not the Florida Courts, if recourse had been sought that out, would not have afforded adequate relief.","start":1972.64,"stop":1981.964,"duration":9.32}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be available at Florida Courts.","start":1981.964,"stop":1985.146,"duration":3.18},{"text":"Children do not lose their rights.","start":1985.146,"stop":1987.311,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there a state equivalent of the Federal Tort Claims Act in Florida?","start":1987.311,"stop":1992.318,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"Not the state equivalent, the school board can be sued, individual, teacher could be sued.","start":1992.318,"stop":1996.338,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no any other course under the Florida Law.","start":1996.338,"stop":1998.43,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Bruce S. Rogow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but this case cannot turn on that issue.","start":1998.43,"stop":2002.355,"duration":3.92},{"text":"If for instance, a prisoner were beaten and everyone can see that that prisoner has the right to hearing if he is being punished by a 100 whacks with a strap, a 100 blows with a strap, he could sue in State Court or Federal Court.","start":2002.355,"stop":2014.437,"duration":12.08},{"text":"If there is an excessive and severe punishment that violates a constitutional right, both courts are equally open, Monroe v. Pape.","start":2014.437,"stop":2020.86,"duration":6.42},{"text":"Children does not lose their rights at the school house door, that was the effect of the Court Of Appeals decision, it went much too far.","start":2020.86,"stop":2027.864,"duration":7},{"text":"We submit that when children are in school, they are in custody of school authorities, of people acting under color of state law and those persons are bound by the constitution.","start":2027.864,"stop":2037.78,"duration":9.92},{"text":"And, for those reasons that the decision below should be reversed.","start":2037.78,"stop":2041.665,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, gentlemen.","start":2041.665,"stop":2042.595,"duration":0.93},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":2042.595,"stop":2044.682,"duration":2.09}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Nov  2 - 3, 1976","petitioner":"James Ingraham, Roosevelt Andrews","respondent":"Willie J. Wright, Lemmie Deliford, Solomon Barnes, Edward L. Whigham","docket":"75-6527","citation":"430 US 651 (1977)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/430/651","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"May 24, 1976","decidedOn":"Apr 19, 1977"}